03941nam a22005295i 9780520967984DE-B159720191221113333.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191221s2018    cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209679847 a10.1525/97805209679842doi  a(DE-B1597)519609  a(OCoLC)1005782710  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aNAT0280002bisacsh1 aShine, Rick, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.10aCane Toad Wars /cRick Shine. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aOrganisms and Environments ;v1500tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tForeword / rGreene, Harry W. -- tPreface -- t1. An Ecological Catastrophe -- t2. How the Cane Toad Came to Australia -- t3. Arrival of Cane Toads at Fogg Dam -- t4. How Cane Toads Have Adapted and Dispersed -- t5. The Impact of Cane Toads on Australian Wildlife -- t6. How the Ecosystem Has Fought Back -- t7. Citizens Take On the Toad -- t8. The Quest for a Way to Control the Toad -- t9. A New Toolkit for Fighting the Toad -- t10. Toad Control Moves from the Lab to the Field -- t11. What We've Learned -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix -- tBibliography and Suggested Reading -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1935, an Australian government agency imported 101 specimens of the Central and South American Cane Toad in an attempt to manage insects that were decimating sugar-cane harvests. In Australia the Cane Toad adapted and evolved with abandon, voraciously consuming native wildlife and killing predators with its lethal skin toxin. Today, hundreds of millions of Cane Toads have spread across the northern part of Australia and continue to move westward. The humble Cane Toad has become a national villain.  Cane Toad Wars chronicles the work of intrepid scientist Rick Shine, who has been documenting the toad's ecological impact in Australia and seeking to buffer it. Despite predictions of devastation in the wake of advancing toad hordes, the author's research reveals a more complex and nuanced story. A firsthand account of a perplexing ecological problem and an important exploration of how we measure evolutionary change and ecological resilience, this book makes an effective case for the value of long-term natural history research in informing conservation practice.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 0aBiological invasionszAustralia. 0aBufo marinuszAustralia. 7aNATURE / Animals / Reptiles & Amphibians.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2018z978311066767708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520967984423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520967984.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066767-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles